BRONCHITIS-\par
\b0 Symptoms\par
For either acute bronchitis or chronic bronchitis, signs and symptoms may include:\par
Cough\par
Production of mucus (sputum), which can be clear, white, yellowish-gray or green in color \f1\emdash  rarely, it may be streaked with blood\par
Fatigue\par
Shortness of breath\par
Slight fever and chills\par
Chest discomfort\par
If you have acute bronchitis, you might have cold symptoms, such as a mild headache or body aches. While these symptoms usually improve in about a week, you may have a nagging cough that lingers for several weeks.\par
Chronic bronchitis is defined as a productive cough that lasts at least three months, with recurring bouts occurring for at least two consecutive years.\par
If you have chronic bronchitis, you're likely to have periods when your cough or other symptoms worsen. At those times, you may have an acute infection on top of chronic bronchitis.\par
\b See your doctor if your cough:\b0\par
Lasts more than three weeks\par
Prevents you from sleeping\par
Is accompanied by fever higher than 100.4 F (38 C)\par
Produces discolored mucus\par
Produces blood\par
Is associated with wheezing or shortness of breath\par
